19,"Lake","Chilika","Odisha",19.716664,85.316667,"Historically, the Chilika region shows human activity from Neolithic times, with Golabai Sasan revealing early boat-building and maritime trade. Ancient Greek and Roman texts potentially reference it as a major port, while medieval accounts highlight its role in sea voyages to Southeast Asia before its gradual separation from the sea. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chilika_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Chilika occupies a vital place in Odisha’s cultural and spiritual imagination, especially through the Kalijai Temple, where the deity is worshipped as the lake’s protector. Local legends, boatmen’s lore, and regional festivals like Makar Sankranti sustain its role as a living sacred landscape for coastal and fishing communities. <br><br> <a href='https://www.chilika.com/chilika-history.php' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Chilika occupies a significant place in maritime textual memories and regional literature, notably in Radhanath Ray’s poetry, where it is celebrated as a source of aesthetic beauty and regional pride. These literary associations frame the lake as a mythic and romanticized landscape, deeply embedding it in the Odia literary imagination. <br><br> <a href='https://scispace.com/pdf/maritime-heritage-in-and-around-chilika-lake-orissa-2t9mx4i5oy.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Chilika Lake faces threats from siltation, illegal prawn farming, and shifting salinity, which disrupt its fragile brackish ecosystem. These pressures, alongside overfishing and pollution, endanger migratory birds, Irrawaddy dolphins, and the livelihoods of fishing communities, requiring urgent conservation to preserve its status as a critical Ramsar site. <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/296786601_Integrated_Sustainable_environmental_Conservation_of_Ansupa_lake_A_famous_water_resource_of_orissa_India' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/Chilika.png"
20,"Channel","Tolly's Nullah (Adi Ganga)","West Bengal",22.4764,88.3458,"Historically, Tolly’s Nullah, or the Adi Ganga, was the original course of the Ganges until the 15th-16th century. In 1777, Major William Tolly re-excavated it to create a navigable trade link between the Hooghly and eastern Bengal, transforming it from a sacred river into a vital colonial-era waterway. <br><br> <a href='https://www.societylanguageculture.org/adminpanel/slc-research/slc-research-details/slc-research-details-add/slc-research-details-update/upload/133.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Spiritually, the Adi Ganga is revered as the 'Original Ganges' and the sacred 'Antarganga.' Historically, it is the actual path of the Ganga flowing towards the sea. Its banks are lined with significant temples and ghats, like Kalighat, making it a central axis of ritual life, ancestral rites, and spiritual geography for Kolkata. <br><br> <a href='https://www.livingwatersmuseum.org/adi-ganga-enmeshed-water-heritage-of-kolkata' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tolly’s Nullah, or the Adi Ganga, appears as a contested space where sacred identity meets urban decay. Literary and historical accounts trace its transition from a revered Puranic river to a neglected colonial canal, framing its decline as a metaphor for the loss of environmental and cultural heritage in Kolkata. <br><br> <a href='https://scientificresearchjournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Social-Science-5_A-1347-1353-Full-Paper.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tolly’s Nullah, or the Adi Ganga, faces catastrophic environmental degradation from untreated sewage discharge, solid waste dumping, and encroachment. These pressures have effectively turned the sacred waterway into a stagnant sewer, leading to extreme pollution, biodiversity loss, and increased public health risks for the surrounding urban population today. <br><br> <a href='https://dialogue.earth/en/pollution/adi-ganga-disappears' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/tollys.png"
21,"Lake","Tampara","Odisha",19.416667,85.083333,"Historically, Tampara Lake is a large freshwater wetland in Odisha, formed over time through the interactions of the Rushikulya River and the sea. During the British colonial era, it was valued for its scenic beauty and ecological significance, eventually becoming a prominent landmark in Ganjam district’s environmental and administrative history. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tampara_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://odishatourism.gov.in/content/tourism/en/discover/attractions/lakes-waterfalls/tampara-lake.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.ramsar.org/sites/default/files/documents/library/wwd2007_rpts_india_kanjia.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tampara Lake faces environmental threats from untreated sewage, nutrient runoff, and rising human encroachment. These pressures drive eutrophication, degrade water quality, and disrupt the lake’s biodiversity, particularly its fish and bird habitats. Increasing tourism and waste discharge further intensify the ecological stress on this freshwater wetland system today. <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/344014639_Algal_diversity_of_Kanjiahata_lake_Nandankanan_Odisha_India' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/tampara.png"
22,"Lake","Anshupa","Odisha",20.466667,85.6,"Historically, Anshupa Lake is a prominent horseshoe-shaped oxbow lake formed by the Mahananda River. It was a significant site during the medieval period, with nearby Saranda Garh serving as a strategic fort. Over centuries, the lake has been a central feature of the Cuttack region’s geomorphological and local historical landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anshupa_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Anshupa Lake holds significant cultural and spiritual value, often associated with local legends and the scenic beauty of the Saranda Hills. It is a site for regional recreation and traditional fishing, while its presence in local lore and proximity to historic ruins links the natural landscape with Cuttack’s cultural heritage. <br><br> <a href='https://www.incredibleindia.gov.in/en/odisha/cuttack/ansupa-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Anshupa Lake is celebrated in Odia literature and folk traditions for its serene beauty and ecological richness. Often depicted as a mirror to the surrounding hills, it serves as a poetic symbol of Odisha’s natural landscape, appearing in regional writings that emphasize the aesthetic and affective connection between people and wetlands. <br><br> <a href='https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1x-mJ1v9QBeUNrLBYMtaAA8XiWlNtE3_Za3_voyYDMA4/edit?gid=0' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Anshupa Lake faces severe environmental threats from rapid siltation, weed infestation (like water hyacinth), and agricultural runoff. These issues are shrinking the lake’s area, reducing water depth, and causing eutrophication. Without sustained conservation and dredging, these pressures endanger the lake’s biodiversity and its role as a vital freshwater habitat.","images/ansupa.png"
23,"Lake","Kanjia","Odisha",20.395,85.823611,"Historically, Kanjia Lake (part of Nandankanan) is a significant freshwater wetland in Odisha, once more extensive before urban expansion. It gained prominence in the mid-20th century as part of the Nandankanan Zoological Park. In 2006, it was recognized as a Wetland of International Importance, highlighting its long-term ecological and regional value. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanjia_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://odishatourisms.com/tour-item/kanjia-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/267335166_Environmental_conditions_of_Chilika_Lake_during_pre_and_post_hydrological_intervention_An_overview' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/kanjia.png"
24,"Lake","Upper Lake (Bada Talab)","Madhya Pradesh",23.25,77.4,"Historically, Bhopal’s Upper Lake (Bhojtal) is attributed to the 11th-century Paramara King Bhoja, who built a massive dam across the Kolans River. It remains one of India’s oldest man-made lakes, serving as a critical water source and a symbol of medieval engineering that shaped the city’s urban and environmental history. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhojtal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Bhojtal holds immense cultural and spiritual significance as the lifeblood of Bhopal, often linked to the legendary King Bhoja. It is a site for ritual bathing, festivals, and local heritage, with the massive statue of Raja Bhoja on its bank symbolizing the city’s historical pride and enduring connection to its founding legacy. <br><br> <a href='https://chalbanjare.com/madhya-pradesh-tour-packages-2025-26/upper-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Bhojtal is a central motif in the literary and oral traditions of Bhopal, appearing in regional poems, histories, and travelogues that celebrate its vastness and beauty. As a Ramsar site, it is also framed in scientific and environmental literature as a vital ecosystem, linking medieval engineering with modern conservation narratives. <br><br> <a href='https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/1206' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Bhojtal faces environmental threats from urban sewage inflow, agricultural runoff, and encroachment. These pressures lead to nutrient enrichment, siltation, and declining water quality. While recognized as a Ramsar site, the lake requires continuous management to balance urban water needs with the preservation of its biodiversity and ecological health. <br><br> <a href='https://waterknowledgehub.org/system/files/2021-11/India_Conservation_and_management_of_Bhoj_Wetlands_329.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/bhojtal.png"
25,"Lake","Lower Lake","Madhya Pradesh",23.245833,77.406944,"Historically, Bhopal’s Lower Lake was commissioned in 1794 by Chote Khan, a minister of Nawab Hayat Mohammad Khan, to beautify the city. Built downstream from the Upper Lake, it represents late-18th-century urban planning under the Bhopal State, serving as a secondary reservoir that integrated the city’s water system with its architectural landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_Lake_(Bhopal)' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Lower Lake holds cultural significance as a central part of Bhopal’s historic urban core, often linked to the city’s Nawabi heritage. It is a site for recreation, festivals, and community gatherings, reflecting the shared social life and aesthetic history of the city, while remaining physically and culturally connected to the larger Bhojtal system. <br><br> <a href='https://earth5r.org/reviving-lower-lake-bhopal-earth5rs-blueprint-for-sustainable-urban-water-restoration' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Lower Lake is often referenced in Bhopal’s local history and travel accounts as the aesthetic counterpart to the larger Upper Lake. Its presence in regional narratives emphasizes the city’s unique 'lake city' identity, framing the waterbody as a vital part of the urban landscape that has witnessed Bhopal’s transition through colonial and postcolonial eras. <br><br> <a href='https://www.tripuntold.com/india/madhya-pradesh/bhopal/lower-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Lower Lake faces severe environmental degradation from untreated sewage, solid waste dumping, and high nutrient loading from surrounding dense urban settlements. These pressures cause eutrophication, foul odors, and declining dissolved oxygen levels, threatening aquatic life and posing public health challenges for the city’s historic central area today. <br><br> <a href='https://www.scholarsresearchlibrary.com/articles/assessment-of-water-quality-parameters-of-lower-lake-bhopal.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/lowerlake.png"
26,"Lake","Shahpura","Madhya Pradesh",23.208889,77.419444,"Historically, Shahpura Lake in Bhopal is a man-made reservoir developed in the mid-20th century as part of the city’s expanding urban infrastructure and drainage system. It was designed to manage water flow and provide a scenic public space, reflecting Bhopal’s post-Independence transition into a modern administrative and residential capital. <br><br> <a href='https://wanderlog.com/place/details/10594705/shahpura-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://ebird.org/region/L27685754' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.onefivenine.com/india/villages/Bhopal/Bhopal/Shahpura-Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Shahpura Lake faces serious environmental threats from heavy metal contamination, urban sewage inflow, and excessive nutrient loading. High levels of lead, chromium, and cadmium, alongside eutrophication, have severely degraded water quality and aquatic habitats. These issues, driven by nearby industrial and domestic waste, pose long-term ecological and public health risks. <br><br> <a href='https://stm.bookpi.org/GESERH-V1/article/view/16146' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/shahpura.png"
27,"Lake","Sankhya Sagar","Madhya Pradesh",25.483333,77.65,"Historically, Sakhya Sagar (and Madhav Lake) in Shivpuri was created in the early 20th century (around 1918) by the Scindia rulers of Gwalior to ensure water supply and enhance the royal hunting grounds. Now part of Madhav National Park, it remains a critical heritage site reflecting princely-era water management and landscape aesthetics. <br><br> <a href='https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/2483?__goaway_challenge=meta-refresh&__goaway_id=0e50869365e55523b9b20ff7617fa49a&__goaway_referer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://seawatersports.com/places/madhya-pradesh/sakhya-sagar-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.drishtiias.com/state-pcs-current-affairs/shivpuris-sankhya-sagar-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sakhya Sagar faces environmental threats from invasive water hyacinth, siltation, and nutrient runoff, which drive eutrophication and reduce water depth. These pressures degrade the lake’s health and threaten its role as a Ramsar site, requiring sustained management to protect its biodiversity, particularly its migratory bird populations and marsh crocodile habitats. <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Physico-chemical-characteristics-of-water-of-Sakhya-Sagar-Lake_tbl1_327369082' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/sankhya.png"
28,"Lake","Tawa Reservoir","Madhya Pradesh",22.555556,77.973333,"Historically, the Tawa Reservoir was created by damming the Tawa River, with construction beginning in 1958 and completion in 1978. It was a major post-Independence irrigation and hydroelectric project in Hoshangabad district, designed to transform the region’s agrarian economy and reflecting India’s mid-20th-century vision for large-scale river-valley development. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tawa_Reservoir' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tawa Reservoir holds significant cultural value as a hub for regional tourism and a source of livelihood for local fishing cooperatives. The displaced tribal communities’ struggle for fishing rights in the late 20th century added a deep social and political dimension to the site, linking the reservoir with regional movements for social justice and resource equity. <br><br> <a href='https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/2547' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tawa Reservoir is often featured in environmental and social studies literature, particularly regarding the 'Tawa Matsya Sangh' movement, which highlighted tribal resource rights. It also appears in regional travelogues and nature writing that celebrate the vastness of the waterbody and its integration with the surrounding Satpura landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/2547' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Tawa Reservoir faces environmental threats from soil erosion and sedimentation, which reduce its storage capacity and alter its hydrology. These pressures, along with potential runoff from surrounding agricultural and forested areas, impact the reservoir’s long-term efficiency and ecological balance, requiring integrated catchment management to preserve its role as a vital water resource. <br><br> <a href='https://www.omicsonline.org/open-access-pdfs/soil-erosion-and-sediment-analysis-of-tawa-reservoir-districtnarmadapuram-mp-using-remote-sensing-and-gis.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/tawa.png"
29,"Lake","Yashwant Sagar","Madhya Pradesh",22.75,75.7,"Historically, Yashwant Sagar was commissioned in the early 1930s (completed around 1939) by Maharaja Yashwant Rao Holkar II of Indore to provide a stable water supply for the city. Built on the Gambhir River, it remains a major heritage reservoir reflecting the Holkar State’s 20th-century modernization and urban planning efforts. <br><br> <a href='https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/2495' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://grokipedia.com/page/Yashwant_Sagar' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/368556666_Aquatic_birds_Diversity_at_Yashwant_Nagar_Talaab_Mhow_MP' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Yashwant Sagar faces environmental threats from agricultural runoff, invasive species, and habitat encroachment. These pressures drive nutrient enrichment and degrade the water quality of this Ramsar site. Protecting the reservoir is critical for preserving its rich biodiversity, particularly as a vital habitat for the Sarus Crane and various migratory bird species. <br><br> <a href='https://grokipedia.com/page/Yashwant_Sagar' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/yashwant.png"
30,"Lake","Sirpur","Madhya Pradesh",22.7,75.816667,"Historically, Sirpur Lake in Indore was commissioned in the early 20th century (around 1905) by Maharaja Tukojirao Holkar III to provide water and aesthetic value to the city. It represents the Holkar State’s early efforts in urban water management and has since evolved into a critical ecological site for the Indore region. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sirpur_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.international-climate-initiative.com/en/iki-media/video/sirpur-talaab-lifeline-of-indore-new662764e0c8bb9199270086' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.drishtiias.com/state-pcs-current-affairs/sirpur-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sirpur Lake faces environmental threats from urban encroachment, sewage inflow, and solid waste dumping. These pressures drive eutrophication and degrade the water quality of this Ramsar site. Sustained conservation effort is essential to maintain the lake as a healthy habitat for migratory birds and to preserve its role in the city’s ecological network. <br><br> <a href='https://journal.environcj.in/index.php/ecj/article/view/537' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/sirpur.png"
