37,"Lake","Sudarshan","Gujarat",21.516111,70.457222,"Historically, Sudarshana Lake in Junagadh was a crucial irrigation project initiated during Chandragupta Maurya’s reign and later improved under Emperor Ashoka. Over centuries, rulers like Rudradaman I and Skandagupta also carried out major repairs and dam reconstruction, making it a unique symbol of ancient Indian engineering, statecraft, and water management. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sudarshana_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='http://junagadhgirnar.com/14-sudarshan-lake-junagadh' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sudarshana Lake’s historical and technical significance is preserved in monumental epigraphic records, most notably the Junagadh rock inscription of Rudradaman. These inscriptions serve as vital historical texts, documenting early dam engineering, environmental management, and the political commitment of ancient rulers to regional resource development and public welfare. <br><br> <a href='https://books.google.co.in/books?id=QRsLEQAAQBAJ&dq=sudarshana+lake&pg=PA313&redir_esc=y' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","images/placeholder.png"
38,"Tank","Bindu","Gujarat",23.90883,72.36363,"It is a small artificial tank, even mentioned in Rig-veda and considered pious by Hindus. It is located at Siddhpur of Patan District of Gujarat. Sidhhpur also contains many ancient temples. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siddhpur' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Situated on the Saraswati River, Siddhpur holds deep spiritual significance as a tirtha, particularly known as the site for Matru Shradh (ancestral rites for mothers). Its sacred character is reinforced by local legends of sage Kapila and the presence of historic ghats, making it a critical landscape of Hindu ritual and pilgrimage. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siddhpur' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated","images/Bindu.png"
39,"Lake","Kankaria","Gujarat",23.00627,72.60121,"Sultan Muizz-ud-Din Muhammad Shah II initiated construction of Kankaria Lake in the mid-fifteenth century, and it was completed in 1451 CE. Historically known as Hauz-e-Qutub, it served as a royal retreat and central water body for medieval Ahmedabad, reflecting Indo-Islamic architecture and urban engineering. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kankaria_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kankaria Carnival functions as a civic-cultural celebration of Ahmedabad, where the lake’s historic precinct transforms into a space for public performance, art, and community gathering. This annual event reinforces the lake’s role as a symbol of urban identity, linking the city’s medieval heritage with its modern, vibrant cultural life. <br><br> <a href='https://utsav.gov.in/public/view-event/kankaria-carnival-2025' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kankaria Lake’s literary significance lies in its layered textual presence in medieval chronicles, travelogues, and colonial accounts, which often praise its grand scale and architectural beauty. These references frame the lake as a central site of historical memory, reflecting the shifting social and political landscape of Ahmedabad across centuries. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kankaria_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.facebook.com/TheModiStory/videos/once-the-pride-of-ahmedabad-kankaria-lake-had-slipped-into-neglect-losing-both-c/1360567845271742' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/kankaria.png"
40,"Canal","Kharicut","Gujarat",23.063889,72.653056,"Kharicut Canal is one of the oldest irrigation schemes of Gujarat, linked to Chandola Lake. This British-era infrastructure was crucial for water management in Ahmedabad district, supporting regional agriculture and urban supply. Today, it remains a historical landmark representing early colonial engineering and its long-term impact on the city’s hydraulic landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandola_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","The Vasna Barrage and its associated canal systems, including the Kharicut, appear in urban studies and geographical narratives as transformative thresholds in the Sabarmati landscape. These literary and technical accounts document the city’s evolving relationship with its river and canals, framing water infrastructure as both a functional necessity and a socio-spatial boundary. <br><br> <a href='https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Xt9KHerkrkAC&dq=vasna+barrage&pg=PA165&redir_esc=y' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kharicut Canal faces severe environmental degradation from untreated sewage, solid waste dumping, and illegal industrial discharge. These pressures have turned parts of the historic canal into a polluted drain, leading to foul odors, health hazards, and groundwater contamination. Reviving the canal requires urgent urban waste management and restoration efforts. <br><br> <a href='https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/british-era-kharicut-canal-ahmedabad-9901321' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/kankaria.png"
41,"Lake","Gopi Talav","Gujarat",21.206667,72.835833,"Historically, Gopi Talav in Surat was commissioned around 1510 CE by Malik Gopi, a prominent merchant and governor under the Gujarat Sultanate. It was a grand stepwell-lake complex that served as a major water source and urban landmark, reflecting the city’s medieval prosperity and its integration into global maritime trade networks. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopi_Talav' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=trdRkz6dOZk' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Gopi Talav holds literary and historical significance through its association with the foundational narratives of Surat’s development. References in local chronicles and colonial travel accounts emphasize Malik Gopi’s role and the lake’s architectural grandeur, framing the site as a key text in understanding the city’s medieval urban and social history. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopi_Talav' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","images/gopi.png"
42,"Lake","Sahastraling","Gujarat",23.845,72.119722,"Sahasralinga Tank in Patan was commissioned in the 12th century by the Chaulukya ruler Jayasimha Siddharaja. This massive artificial reservoir, part of the Saraswati river system, featured intricate stone channels and shrines, representing a pinnacle of medieval Indian hydraulic engineering and the sophisticated water-management traditions of the Solanki period. <br><br> <a href='https://patan.nic.in/tourist-place/sahastra-ling-talav' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sahasralinga Tank holds immense cultural and spiritual significance, historically surrounded by a thousand small shrines (lingas) dedicated to Lord Shiva. Although now in ruins, the site remains a major pilgrimage and heritage landmark, embodying the deep ritual and aesthetic connection between water, architecture, and devotion in medieval Gujarat. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sahasralinga_Tank' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sahasralinga Tank is embedded in the literary and folk traditions of Gujarat, most famously through the legend of Jasma Odan, who is said to have cursed the lake. These oral and written narratives add a mythic layer to the site, framing the tank not just as a reservoir but as a space of moral and cultural memory. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sahasralinga_Tank' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/bindu-sarovar-samir-barua-j3xtf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/sahastraling.png"
43,"Lake","Lakhota","Gujarat",22.4764,70.0672,"Historically, Lakhota Lake (or Ranmal Lake) in Jamnagar was commissioned in the mid-19th century by Jam Ranmalji II during a period of severe famine to provide employment and water security. The central Lakhota Palace and the lake itself reflect Jadeja Rajput architecture and 19th-century princely-state urban planning. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhota_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Lakhota Lake holds significant cultural value as the social and spiritual heart of Jamnagar, surrounded by temples and serving as a central site for festivals like Janmashtami. It functions as a public heritage space where community life, local history, and ritual practices converge, reinforcing the lake’s role in the city’s regional identity. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhota_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","Lakhota Lake faces environmental threats from urban sewage inflow and rising human pressure, which impact its water quality and ecological balance. While a major recreational site, the lake requires continuous management to prevent nutrient loading and to preserve its role as a vital urban wetland and habitat for migratory birds. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhota_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/lakhota.png"
44,"Tank","Damodar","Gujarat",21.52585,70.486022,"Historically, Damodar Kund in Junagadh is linked to the Suryavanshi ruler Chandraketpur and was later renovated during Skandagupta’s reign. Situated at the foothills of Girnar, it has served for centuries as a major water body and ritual site, reflecting the deep historical and administrative continuity of Junagadh’s sacred landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_Kund' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Damodar Kund holds major Hindu spiritual significance as a sacred lake where ritual bathing is believed to provide salvation for the departed (Pitru Tarpan). Its proximity to ancient temples and the Girnar pilgrimage circuit makes it a critical site for ancestral rites and spiritual purification, drawing devotees from across India. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_Kund' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Damodar Kund is celebrated in Gujarati literary and devotional history, particularly through its association with the 15th-century poet-saint Narsinh Mehta, who is said to have bathed here. The kund appears in his bhajans and local folk traditions, framing it as a mythic and affective landscape of Vaishnava devotion. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://books.google.co.in/books?id=eRkuXFD93zsC&dq=damodar+kund+girnar&pg=PA38&redir_esc=y' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://books.google.co.in/books?id=eRkuXFD93zsC&dq=damodar+kund+girnar&pg=PA38&redir_esc=y</a></li><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_Kund' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_Kund</a></li></ul>","Visitor accounts and environmental reports indicate that Damodar Kund faces challenges from water pollution and waste management, especially during peak pilgrimage seasons. These pressures threaten the site’s ecological and ritual purity, requiring improved sanitation and sustainable waste disposal to preserve its long-term health as a sacred water body. <br><br> <a href='https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g303879-d2708885-r636371329-Damodar_Kund_Water_Reservoir-Junagadh_Junagadh_District_Gujarat.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/placeholder.png"
45,"Channel","Subarnarekha","Jharkhand",23.3,85.183,"To be updated <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://hindi.news18.com/news/jharkhand/jamshedpur-subarnarekha-swarnarekha-river-length-origin-history-starting-point-local18-ws-l-9848710' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://hindi.news18.com/news/jharkhand/jamshedpur-subarnarekha-swarnarekha-river-length-origin-history-starting-point-local18-ws-l-9848710</a></li><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarnarekha_River' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarnarekha_River</a></li><li><a href='https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_97.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_97.pdf</a></li></ul>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://otibeguni.com/codex/FolkDeityWorshipontheBanksSubarnarekhaRiver' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/the-mystery-behind-subarnrekha-the-river-of-gold-in-jharkhand/articleshow/88026554.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/the-mystery-behind-subarnrekha-the-river-of-gold-in-jharkhand/articleshow/88026554.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://www.grafiati.com/en/literature-selections/subarnarekha-river' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.grafiati.com/en/literature-selections/subarnarekha-river</a></li></ul>","To be updated <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ranchi/jharkhand-subarnarekha-rivers-pollution-level-high-near-jamshedpur/articleshow/91896233.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ranchi/jharkhand-subarnarekha-rivers-pollution-level-high-near-jamshedpur/articleshow/91896233.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://avenuemail.in/jamshedpur-industrial-wastes-adding-to-pollution-level-in-river-subarnarekha' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://avenuemail.in/jamshedpur-industrial-wastes-adding-to-pollution-level-in-river-subarnarekha</a></li><li><a href='https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/poison-ails-subarnarekha-river-finds-survey/cid/1728268' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/poison-ails-subarnarekha-river-finds-survey/cid/1728268</a></li><li><a href='https://publicintegrity.org/national-security/indias-nuclear-industry-pours-its-wastes-into-a-river-of-death-and-disease' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://publicintegrity.org/national-security/indias-nuclear-industry-pours-its-wastes-into-a-river-of-death-and-disease</a></li><li><a href='https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_293.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_293.pdf</a></li></ul>","images/placeholder.png"
