47,"Channel","Narmada Main","Gujarat",23.344444,72.4,"Historically, the Narmada Main Canal is a monumental feat of modern Indian engineering, part of the Sardar Sarovar Project. Initiated in the late 20th century to transform Gujarat’s water security, it remains one of the world’s longest irrigation canals, representing a massive post-Independence infrastructure push to resolve regional water scarcity. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narmada_Canal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://youtu.be/xgu3T0r7u0g?si=9ixsO-AkTgS6ONC4' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated","images/narmadamain.png"
48,"Canal","Ganges","Uttar Pradesh",29.944,78.163,"Historically, the Ganges Canal was a pioneering 19th-century colonial engineering project commissioned by the British and completed in 1854. Designed to provide irrigation and famine protection for the Doab region, it remains one of the world’s most significant historical canal systems, reflecting the large-scale hydraulic interventions of the British Raj. <br><br> <a href='https://pahar.in/pahar/Books%20and%20Articles/Indian%20Subcontinent/1864%20The%20Ganges%20Canal%20--A%20discussion%20by%20Cotton%20and%20Cautley%20s.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganges_Canal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","images/gangescanal.png"
49,"Canal","Halali","Madhya Pradesh",23.504167,77.553333,"Historically, the Halali Dam (and its canal system) was completed in the 1970s on the Halali River in Raisen district. Built primarily for irrigation and flood control, it represents Madhya Pradesh’s mid-20th-century push to expand the agrarian economy, while the river itself carries older legends of 18th-century battles and regional shifts. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halali_Reservoir' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.ijsrp.org/research-paper-1212/ijsrp-p12102.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Halali Reservoir is featured in environmental and ichthyofaunal literature, which documents its diverse fish populations and ecological health. These technical narratives frame the reservoir as a vital freshwater system, linking irrigation infrastructure with modern biodiversity research and the study of regional aquatic ecosystems in Madhya Pradesh. <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/371491062_Ichthyofaunal_diversity_of_Halali_reservoir_Vidisha_MP' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Halali Dam region faces environmental threats from heavy metal contamination and potential runoff from surrounding agricultural areas. These pressures degrade water quality and aquatic habitats, posing risks to the reservoir’s biodiversity and its role as a stable water source, requiring sustained monitoring and integrated environmental management today. <br><br> <a href='https://www.cwejournal.org/vol1no1/study-of-heavy-metal-contamination-in-halali-dam-water-of-vidisha-distrcit-near-bhopal-m-p-india-with-reference-to-humam-health' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/halali.png"
