55,"Channel","Subarnarekha Canal","West Bengal",22.466667,86.733333,"To be updated","Subarnarekha River and its canal system hold cultural significance, particularly through community-led restoration efforts like those in Kulachada. These initiatives link the river with regional agrarian heritage and folk resilience, framing the waterway as a vital communal resource that sustains both the spiritual and material life of rural Bengal and Jharkhand. <br><br> <a href='https://goonj.org/grassroots-innovations/kulachada-canal-restoration-subarnarekha-river' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Subarnarekha River and its canals are celebrated in literature, most notably in the works of Bibhutibhushan Bandyopadhyay, where they symbolize the raw beauty and mystery of the regional landscape. These literary associations frame the waterway as a mythic and emotional space, deeply embedding it in the cultural memory of eastern India. <br><br> <a href='https://wbiwd.gov.in/index.php/applications/subarnarekha' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","images/SubernarekhaMultipurposeProject.png"
56,"Channel","Mahananda Canal","West Bengal",26.7,88.4,"To be updated","To be updated","To be updated","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://www.academia.edu/120556152/Effects_of_Fulbari_Mahananda_Barrage_on_the_Channel_Morphology_of_the_Mahananda_River_in_Terai_Region_West_Bengal_India' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/placeholder.png"
57,"Channel","Damodar","Jharkhand",23.671709,85.759419,"Historically, the Damodar was infamous as Bengal’s 'River of Sorrows' due to catastrophic floods, leading to the creation of the Damodar Valley Corporation (DVC) in 1948. Modeled on the Tennessee Valley Authority, this project was India’s first major multipurpose river valley development, marking a pivotal shift in post-Independence infrastructure and resource management. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://srishtisandhan.com/Srishtisandhan/Art/SSAN22PDamodarRamaKundu.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://srishtisandhan.com/Srishtisandhan/Art/SSAN22PDamodarRamaKundu.pdf</a></li><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_River' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_River</a></li><li><a href='https://www.1bhaskar.com/damodar' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.1bhaskar.com/damodar</a></li><li><a href='https://indiageomorph.org/uploads/pdf/Impact-of-Dam-on-River-Discharge-A-Study-on-the-Damodar-River,-Jharkhand-by-Sahidul-Karim-and-Sunil-Kumar-De.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://indiageomorph.org/uploads/pdf/Impact-of-Dam-on-River-Discharge-A-Study-on-the-Damodar-River,-Jharkhand-by-Sahidul-Karim-and-Sunil-Kumar-De.pdf</a></li></ul>","Rajrappa’s cultural and spiritual significance centers on the Chhinnamasta Temple, situated at the confluence of the Damodar and Bhera rivers. This ancient Shakti Peeth, with its distinct iconography, makes the riverbanks a vital sacred landscape for tantric worship, pilgrimage, and ritual life, deeply intertwining natural flow with spiritual energy. <br><br> <a href='https://www.poojn.in/post/17118/rajrappas-natural-beauty-damodar-river-and-beyond-a-complete-guide' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Damodar appears in Indian literature and historical memory through narratives of suffering and resilience, particularly regarding its devastating floods. In contemporary literature, such as Shelina Hossain’s 'Budhini,' the river system becomes a metaphor for tribal displacement and the social costs of mid-20th-century modernization and large-scale dam construction. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.penguin.co.in/book/budhini' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.penguin.co.in/book/budhini</a></li><li><a href='https://www.ibpbooks.in/on-the-banks-of-damodar/p/41085' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.ibpbooks.in/on-the-banks-of-damodar/p/41085</a></li></ul>","The Damodar faces severe environmental threats from heavy industrial pollution, coal mining runoff, and ash slurry discharge. These pressures have led to high levels of oil, grease, and heavy metals in the water, degrading aquatic habitats and endangering the health of millions of residents who depend on this 'Sorrow of Bengal' system. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/damodar-river-pollution-waste-oil-jharia-coalfields-bokaro-1609744-2019-10-15' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/damodar-river-pollution-waste-oil-jharia-coalfields-bokaro-1609744-2019-10-15</a></li><li><a href='https://india.mongabay.com/2021/09/the-sorrow-of-damodar-river-continues-for-millions-of-people' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://india.mongabay.com/2021/09/the-sorrow-of-damodar-river-continues-for-millions-of-people</a></li><li><a href='https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/purity-undermined-14836' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/purity-undermined-14836</a></li></ul>","images/damodorchannel.png"
58,"Channel","Subarnarekha","Jharkhand",23.3,85.183,"The Subarnarekha (meaning 'Streak of Gold') derives its name from traditions of gold mining near its origin at Piska. Historically, the river has been a vital lifeline for the Chota Nagpur plateau, witnessing the region’s transition from tribal agrarian landscapes to a major industrial hub with the rise of Jamshedpur. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://hindi.news18.com/news/jharkhand/jamshedpur-subarnarekha-swarnarekha-river-length-origin-history-starting-point-local18-ws-l-9848710' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://hindi.news18.com/news/jharkhand/jamshedpur-subarnarekha-swarnarekha-river-length-origin-history-starting-point-local18-ws-l-9848710</a></li><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarnarekha_River' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subarnarekha_River</a></li><li><a href='https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_97.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_97.pdf</a></li></ul>","Folk deity worship on the banks of the Subarnarekha reflects a syncretic spiritual culture, where tribal traditions and local Hindu practices converge. The river is central to regional festivals and ritual bathing, embodying a living sacredness that sustains the identity and communal heritage of the people across Jharkhand, West Bengal, and Odisha. <br><br> <a href='https://otibeguni.com/codex/FolkDeityWorshipontheBanksSubarnarekhaRiver' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Subarnarekha has been transformed from a geographical river into a cultural text, appearing as a site of mystery and beauty in regional literature. Most notably, it serves as the backdrop for iconic works in Bengali and tribal lore, framing the waterway as a mythic space of golden potential and deep environmental memory. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/the-mystery-behind-subarnrekha-the-river-of-gold-in-jharkhand/articleshow/88026554.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/the-mystery-behind-subarnrekha-the-river-of-gold-in-jharkhand/articleshow/88026554.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://www.grafiati.com/en/literature-selections/subarnarekha-river' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.grafiati.com/en/literature-selections/subarnarekha-river</a></li></ul>","The Subarnarekha faces severe environmental threats from industrial effluents, urban sewage, and radioactive slurry leaks from uranium mining. These pollutants, combined with heavy metal contamination and invasive species, have degraded its water quality and biodiversity, posing serious health risks and ecological stress on this vital regional river system. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ranchi/jharkhand-subarnarekha-rivers-pollution-level-high-near-jamshedpur/articleshow/91896233.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ranchi/jharkhand-subarnarekha-rivers-pollution-level-high-near-jamshedpur/articleshow/91896233.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://avenuemail.in/jamshedpur-industrial-wastes-adding-to-pollution-level-in-river-subarnarekha' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://avenuemail.in/jamshedpur-industrial-wastes-adding-to-pollution-level-in-river-subarnarekha</a></li><li><a href='https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/poison-ails-subarnarekha-river-finds-survey/cid/1728268' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/poison-ails-subarnarekha-river-finds-survey/cid/1728268</a></li><li><a href='https://publicintegrity.org/national-security/indias-nuclear-industry-pours-its-wastes-into-a-river-of-death-and-disease' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://publicintegrity.org/national-security/indias-nuclear-industry-pours-its-wastes-into-a-river-of-death-and-disease</a></li><li><a href='https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_293.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://appforest.jharkhand.gov.in/fresearch/admin/file/research_293.pdf</a></li></ul>","images/SubernarekhaMultipurposeProject.png"
