60,"Channel","Mayurakshi","West Bengal",23.661389,87.611389,"Historically, the Mayurakshi-Kuya interfluve showed two major right-bank bifurcations before 1916. Between 1917 and 1968, additional secondary bifurcations and natural linkings developed. Later, Massanjore Dam (1956), Tilpara Barrage (1971), and an embankment built in 1995 altered older channels, accelerating drying, agricultural encroachment, and wetland decline across the region over time. <br><br> <a href='https://indiageomorph.org/uploads/pdf/JoIG-v2-(2013)-p037-045-Mukhopadhyay--Das---Channel-deranging-in-Mayurakshi-Kuya-interfluve.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Mayurakshi River holds marked cultural and spiritual significance in eastern India. Local traditions associate it with the goddess Mayurakshi, believed to have bathed in its waters. The river appears in regional folk songs and poems, while temples along its banks and the annual Mayurakshi Mela sustain its ritual prominence today. <br><br> <a href='https://seawatersports.com/places/jharkhand/mayurakshi-river' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Mayurakshi as a river of memory, legend, and shifting historical identity. It links the river with Karnasubarna, Mahabharata’s Subarnabaluka, abandoned channels like Kana Mayurakshi, and place-names preserving cultural remembrance, thereby framing fluvial change as both environmental and narrative history in Bengal. <br><br> <a href='https://www.academia.edu/122329182/Mayurakshi_River_Water_Resources_and_Environment' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The study identifies nutrient pollution as the principal environmental threat to the Mayurakshi River system. Excess phosphate in surface waters promotes eutrophication, while nitrate overload further intensifies ecological stress. These pollutants are mainly linked to agricultural fertilizer runoff, domestic waste discharge, animal feedlot runoff, and other anthropogenic sources across sites. <br><br> <a href='https://www.internationaljournalssrg.org/IJAES/2017/Volume4-Issue4/IJAES-V4I4P109.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/placeholder.png"
61,"Channel","Kharkai","Jharkhand",22.8354,86.16125,"Historically, the Kharkai River has been associated with the agrarian landscape of its lower valley, where rice cultivation dominated, and with the later industrial expansion of Jamshedpur, marked by the establishment of a major steel plant. Mid-twentieth-century economic and cartographic records also document the river’s regional importance in eastern India. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kharkai_River' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Kharkai River holds considerable cultural and spiritual significance in Jamshedpur, especially during festivals such as Durga Puja and Chhath, when it becomes a key ritual site. Beyond its practical value, the river embodies collective pride, sacredness, and regional identity, meaningfully linking ecological preservation with cultural continuity and community memory. <br><br> <a href='https://avenuemail.in/cleanliness-of-jamshedpurs-kharkai-river-a-shared-responsibility' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Pradip Dasgupta’s “Jharkhand” constructs a regional lyric through repetitive first-person assertion, catalogic listing, and vivid nature imagery. The poem personifies homeland as maternal space, intertwining ecology, tribal culture, rivers, minerals, flowers, and festivals. Its literary value lies in place-based identity formation and the fusion of landscape with deeply affective belonging. <br><br> <a href='https://www.poemhunter.com/poem/jharkhand' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Kharkai and Subarnarekha river system faces severe environmental threats from industrial effluents, urban sewage, agricultural runoff, and metal laden wastewater. These pollutants raise cyanide, lead, and iron levels, stimulate invasive water hyacinth growth, reduce dissolved oxygen, block sunlight, restrict flow, degrade aquatic habitats, and endanger fish, flora, and biodiversity. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://tunza.eco-generation.org/ambassadorReportView.jsp?viewID=57276' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://tunza.eco-generation.org/ambassadorReportView.jsp?viewID=57276</a></li><li><a href='https://www.jetir.org/papers/JETIR2307791.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.jetir.org/papers/JETIR2307791.pdf</a></li><li><a href='https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/let-s-pray-for-this-green-green-river/cid/1429202' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/let-s-pray-for-this-green-green-river/cid/1429202</a></li></ul>","images/kharkai.png"
62,"Canal","Kanchi","Jharkhand",23.218208,85.797714,"Approved by the Planning Commission in 1953, the Kanchi Major Irrigation Project was formulated during India’s Second Five-Year Plan (1956–61), taken up in 1958, and completed in 1966. Planned at Rs 0.93 crore, it was finished at an actual cost of Rs 1.52 crore in Jharkhand’s Ranchi area. <br><br> <a href='https://indiawris.gov.in/wiki/doku.php?id=kanchi_major_irrigation_project_ji02295' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated","The Kanchi River and its canal project face environmental threats from aging infrastructure and erratic water supply, which impact regional agriculture and farmers' livelihoods. These pressures, combined with potential ecological changes in the river basin, highlight the need for modernization and sustainable management to preserve the project’s role as a vital irrigation resource in Jharkhand. <br><br> <a href='https://en.gaonconnection.com/english/jharkhand-farmers-canal-kanchi-river-canal-project-irrigation-water-supply-agriculture-farming-51722' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/kanchi.png"
63,"Lake","Dimna","Jharkhand",22.863105,86.261562,"Dimna Lake emerged from Jamshedpur’s late-1930s response to growing water scarcity. Under the Dimna Nala Water Supply Scheme, Tata Steel began construction in February 1940 in Boram block. The reservoir was completed in 1944, and on 17 April that year, it supplied water to the city for the first time. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimna_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Dimna Lake’s cultural significance lies chiefly in its connection with Jharkhand’s tribal heritage, where visitors encounter local festivals, dance, and cuisine as part of the tourism experience. Although not framed as a formal pilgrimage site, its tranquil landscape fosters reflection and contemplation, adding a subtle spiritual dimension to the place. <br><br> <a href='https://travelsetu.com/guide/dimna-lake-tourism/dimna-lake-tourism-history' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated <br><br> <a href='https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/20b9/358bba43d093f5d136e1904f1bf447a6a9a0.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Dimna Lake faces serious environmental degradation from unchecked dumping of thermocol plates, plastic cups, liquor bottles and food waste along its banks and in the water. Floating picnic leftovers, accumulated filth, absent dustbins and irregular cleaning are turning the lake into a polluted trash zone, threatening its ecological health overall. <br><br> <a href='https://www.telegraphindia.com/jharkhand/dimna-lake-cries-for-attention/cid/1342852' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/dimna.png"
64,"Lake","Udhwa","Jharkhand",24.992361,87.809306,"Historically, Udhwa is significant for the Battle of Udhwa Nala in 1763, fought between Nawab Mir Qasim of Bengal and the British. Mir Qasim was defeated here and fled with his family toward Rohtas in Bihar. The episode links Udhwa to the wider history of British expansion in eastern India. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udhwa' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","To be updated","Udhwa Lake faces severe ecological threats from agricultural expansion, illegal settlements, fertilizer and pesticide runoff, domestic waste inflows, illegal fishing, bird poaching, deforestation, encroachment, and siltation. These pressures drive nutrient enrichment, chemical contamination, eutrophication, oxygen depletion, habitat degradation, reduced wetland area, disrupted water flow, biodiversity loss, and declining fish populations. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.keybiodiversityareas.org/site/factsheet/18179' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.keybiodiversityareas.org/site/factsheet/18179</a></li><li><a href='https://www.multisubjectjournal.com/article/815/7-10-39-609.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.multisubjectjournal.com/article/815/7-10-39-609.pdf</a></li></ul>","images/udhwa.png"
65,"Channel","Punpun Flood","Bihar",25.511239,85.311175,"Historically, the Punpun is linked in traditional memory to ancient Magadh, the Garuda Purana, and Lord Rama’s pind daan, while a centuries-old ritual sequence places first ancestral offerings on its banks. The basin also preserves deep antiquity, with Archaean-era rocks and ancient crystalline formations in its southern landscape still today. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punpun_River' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punpun_River</a></li><li><a href='https://ijarse.com/images/fullpdf/1602918225_T906.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://ijarse.com/images/fullpdf/1602918225_T906.pdf</a></li></ul>","Spiritually, the Punpun River is revered as the former “Adi Ganga,” linked to Punpuniya’s penance and Vishnu’s grace, which endowed it with salvific power. Culturally, Punpun town is associated with the first Pind Daan, while Pitru Paksha rites and the Varuni Mela sustain its enduring ritual significance in Bihar today. <br><br> <a href='https://gyanganga.ai/admin/fileupload/Punpun%20river.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Punpun emerges as a mythopoetic river text: the travel narrative links it to the Vayu and Padma Puranas through the etymology punah-punah, while the ETV Bharat account frames it through Brahma, the Saptarishis, and Rama’s ancestral rites, embedding the river within Purāṇic memory, narrative, epic imagination, and collective consciousness. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://seth-traveldiary.blogspot.com/2017/09/have-we-missed-opportunity-to-visit.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://seth-traveldiary.blogspot.com/2017/09/have-we-missed-opportunity-to-visit.html</a></li><li><a href='https://www.etvbharat.com/hindi/bihar/state/patna/know-why-punpun-is-called-adi-ganga-and-how-pind-daan-started/bh20220907125407532532248' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.etvbharat.com/hindi/bihar/state/patna/know-why-punpun-is-called-adi-ganga-and-how-pind-daan-started/bh20220907125407532532248</a></li></ul>","Punpun River faces major environmental threats from untreated domestic sewage discharged through Bakipur Gorakh and Badshahi drains, high faecal coliform contamination, and the absence of a sewerage network or STP. Seasonal heavy rains further intensify flood damage and urban waterlogging around Patna, increasing ecological stress and vulnerability for nearby residents. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://forestonline.bihar.gov.in/RRC/Docs/Action%20Plan%20of%20Punpun%20River.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://forestonline.bihar.gov.in/RRC/Docs/Action%20Plan%20of%20Punpun%20River.pdf</a></li><li><a href='https://telanganatoday.com/patna-faces-flood-threat-as-ganga-punpun-rivers-flow-above-danger-level' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://telanganatoday.com/patna-faces-flood-threat-as-ganga-punpun-rivers-flow-above-danger-level</a></li></ul>","images/placeholder.png"
66,"Channel","Saryu Sahayak Link","Uttar Pradesh",28.2725,81.086944,"Conceived in 1972 and initiated in 1978, the Saryu Canal Project was originally designed to irrigate 3.12 lakh hectares in Bahraich and Gonda. Expanded in 1982, it eventually covered nine districts. Delayed for decades by land acquisition and budget shortages, the project was finally completed after forty-five years in 2023 <br><br> <a href='https://www.kisantak.in/crops/uttar-press/story/after-45-years-saryu-canal-project-become-lifeline-for-29-lakhs-farmers-of-purvanchal-631020-2023-08-17' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Saryu Ghat functions as a sacred cultural landscape in Ayodhya, where mythology, ritual bathing, temple worship, and festivals such as Ram Navami and Deepotsav sustain collective memory and devotional practice. Associated with Lord Rama’s jal samadhi, the river symbolizes spiritual purification, communal solidarity, and the continuity of inherited Hindu traditions. <br><br> <a href='https://www.iosrjournals.org/iosr-jagg/papers/Vol.%2010%20Issue%205/Ser-1/H1005015459.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","Environmental threats in the Saryu region include untreated sewage, idol immersion waste, agricultural runoff, eutrophication, oxygen depletion, and bacterial contamination in the river. The Saryu Canal project further risks waterlogging, salinization, flooding, seepage, sedimentation, high water tables, and destruction of cropland, forests, and nearby wildlife habitats through permanent ecological degradation. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.zoologyjournals.com/assets/archives/2025/vol10issue3/10061.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.zoologyjournals.com/assets/archives/2025/vol10issue3/10061.pdf</a></li><li><a href='https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/environmental-conservation/article/abs/evaluation-of-environmental-impacts-of-saryu-canal-in-india/468839811AC44021FF2A7D143498260D' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/environmental-conservation/article/abs/evaluation-of-environmental-impacts-of-saryu-canal-in-india/468839811AC44021FF2A7D143498260D</a></li></ul>","images/Saryu.png"
67,"Pond","Surha","Uttar Pradesh",25.75,84.3333,"Historically, Surha Taal emerged through the consolidation of land from 45 villages in Ballia and later came to be known as Jai Prakash Narain Bird Sanctuary, though locals still retain its earlier name. The site carries legends reflecting historical, traditional, and religious associations, and was declared a sanctuary in 1991. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surha_Tal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surha_Tal</a></li><li><a href='https://upecoboard.up.gov.in/en/article/jai-prakash-narain-bird-sanctuary' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://upecoboard.up.gov.in/en/article/jai-prakash-narain-bird-sanctuary</a></li></ul>","To be updated","Suraha Tal is celebrate in regional and scientific literature, which documents its role as a vital floodplain wetland and bird sanctuary. These narratives frame the site as a space of biodiversity and local heritage, linking the natural history of the wetland with technical studies on its avian populations and ecological sustainability. <br><br> <a href='https://mset-biospectra.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/183-188.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Suraha Tal wetland faces severe ecological threat from illegal university and waste-disposal construction within a protected bird sanctuary, blocking natural water channels, disrupting hydrology, and harming bird habitats. Existing pressures—overfishing, weed infestation, and excessive drainage—further degrade this biodiverse floodplain wetland and intensify long-term ecological vulnerability across the entire sanctuary. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/daily-court-digest-major-environment-orders-september-22-2025' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/daily-court-digest-major-environment-orders-september-22-2025</a></li><li><a href='https://sandrp.in/2022/05/21/uttar-pradesh-govt-builds-university-in-suraha-tal-wetlands' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://sandrp.in/2022/05/21/uttar-pradesh-govt-builds-university-in-suraha-tal-wetlands</a></li></ul>","images/surha.png"
68,"Pond","Gobind Ballabh Pant","Uttar Pradesh",24.2025,83.008056,"Rihand Dam, on the Rihand River in Sonbhadra, emerged from colonial-era planning, as British authorities considered a dam there by 1940. After Independence, the Indian government sanctioned surveys in 1952; construction began in 1954 and ended in 1962, reflecting Jawaharlal Nehru’s postcolonial nation-building and infrastructure vision for modern India thereafter. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rihand_Dam' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Sonbhadra’s cultural-spiritual significance rests on its associations with the Ramayana and Mahabharata, its cave-dwelling early communities, and its historical reputation as a “second Kashi” between the eleventh and thirteenth centuries. The district also preserves layered traditions through Vijaygarh and Agori forts, reflecting enduring sacred-historical memory within the region’s cultural landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://sonbhadra.nic.in/history' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","The Rihand Dam and Gobind Ballabh Pant Sagar are documented in technical and environmental literature, which evaluates their role in regional energy production and ecological impact. These narratives frame the reservoir as a critical post-Independence infrastructure, linking large-scale engineering with the study of water quality and industrial stress in the Sonbhadra landscape. <br><br> <a href='https://ijsr.in/upload/1257417002Chapt_15.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Serious environmental threats linked to the Rihand Dam region, including industrial wastewater, mercury contamination, fly ash, ash slurry, cement dust, and harmful gases such as sulphur dioxide and hydrogen fluoride. In addition, coal mining, waste dumps, and declining water quality have severely affected the local aquatic environment and ecosystems. <br><br> <a href='https://www.ijsrp.org/research-paper-1112/ijsrp-p1158.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/govind.png"
69,"Pond","Sheesh Mahal","Uttar Pradesh",26.87339,80.907692,"Lucknow’s historical landscape preserves centuries-old stepwells, tanks, and monuments shaped by Nawabi, Mughal, and colonial interventions. Structures such as Shahi Bawali, Husainabad, Satkhanda, and Sheesh Mahal reflect evolving water management, royal patronage, architectural synthesis, and later British additions, revealing the layered urban history of the city across time and memory. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/celebrating-250-years-of-lucknows-legacy-baolis-stepwell-to-awadhi-architectural-legacy/articleshow/124756091.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/celebrating-250-years-of-lucknows-legacy-baolis-stepwell-to-awadhi-architectural-legacy/articleshow/124756091.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/lucknow-news/heritage-aficionados-take-a-walk-through-lucknow-s-historical-landmarks-and-learn-untold-stories-of-the-city-s-past-101686487298031.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/lucknow-news/heritage-aficionados-take-a-walk-through-lucknow-s-historical-landmarks-and-learn-untold-stories-of-the-city-s-past-101686487298031.html</a></li></ul>","To be updated","To be updated","Sheesh Mahal pond faces severe environmental stress from prolonged sewage and household waste inflow, which turned it into a polluted dump. Excessive pumping during cleaning also lowered the surrounding groundwater table. Faulty sewer construction, absent drainage networks, waterlogging, and disease-causing microbes further worsened the pond’s ecological and public health condition. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/cleaning-of-sheesh-mahal-pond-in-old-city-leads-to-depleting-water-level/articleshow/35359042.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/cleaning-of-sheesh-mahal-pond-in-old-city-leads-to-depleting-water-level/articleshow/35359042.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/sewerage-trickling-into-sheesh-mahal-pond/articleshow/47155280.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/sewerage-trickling-into-sheesh-mahal-pond/articleshow/47155280.cms</a></li></ul>","images/seesh.png"
70,"Pond","Surajkund","Uttar Pradesh",26.7667,83.3556,"Gorakhpur’s Suryakund is regarded as an ancient heritage site and one of India’s twenty-six historic Sun ponds. Tradition holds that Raja Man Singh built it in 1458 for the worship of Surya and other deities. The site is also linked to textual memory through references associated with the Valmiki Ramayana. <br><br> <a href='https://www.amarujala.com/gorakhpur/suryakund-located-in-gorakhpur-is-one-of-26-suryakunds-of-country-2023-04-18?pageId=1' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Surajkund Lake in Gorakhpur, also known as Surajkund Dham, holds cultural and spiritual significance as a historic sacred pond dedicated to Lord Sun (Suryadev) and Rama. Its surrounding temple environment and meditative atmosphere make it a valued site of devotion, reflection, and local religious reverence within the city's living heritage. <br><br> <a href='https://bharatsair.com/places-to-visit-in-gorakhpur/surajkund-lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","Surajkund Pond faces serious environmental stress from anthropogenic pollution. Organic loading has pushed the waterbody toward a eutrophic condition, while elevated BOD and COD indicate degraded water quality. Recent oil and grease contamination, intensified by ritual offerings, formed a surface film, reduced oxygen transfer, and caused fish suffocation and mortality. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/varanasi/oil-presence-in-surajkund-pond-killed-fish-report/articleshow/125142845.cms' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/varanasi/oil-presence-in-surajkund-pond-killed-fish-report/articleshow/125142845.cms</a></li><li><a href='https://www.academia.edu/6098107/Assessment_of_Physico_chemical_Water_Quality_Parameters_of_Surajkund_Pondin_Gorakhpur_City' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.academia.edu/6098107/Assessment_of_Physico_chemical_Water_Quality_Parameters_of_Surajkund_Pondin_Gorakhpur_City</a></li></ul>","images/sarjukunda.png"
71,"Lake","Kanwar","Bihar",25.61,86.14,"Kanwar Lake Bird Sanctuary, in Begusarai, Bihar, was established in 1987, though the lake itself originated in the geological past through the meandering Burhi Gandak River. Its historical significance deepened when ornithologist Salim Ali documented migratory and resident birds there, and when it gained Ramsar protection in 2020 official status. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kanwar_Lake_Bird_Sanctuary' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kanwar Lake possesses marked cultural and spiritual significance through the ancient Jaimangla temple on its bank, dedicated to the goddess Jaimangal (Durga/Bhavani). The site’s sacred aura is reinforced by archaeological remains, including terracotta objects, coins, idol fragments, and Gupta-period seals, which collectively attest to its long-standing ritual-historical importance in Bihar. <br><br> <a href='https://neptjournal.com/upload-images/(8)B-4060.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kanwar Lake’s literary significance in the article emerges through its association with Manjhaul, birthplace of Rashtrakavi Ramdhari Singh Dinkar, and through Mahesh Bharti’s vernacular, memory-driven narration. Bharti’s authorship of a book on the lake further frames the wetland as a culturally remembered and textually mediated landscape within regional public discourse. <br><br> <a href='https://www.localsamosa.com/people-culture/bihars-only-ramsar-site-kanwar-lake-i-10601520' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Kanwar Lake faces severe ecological threats from rapid drying, siltation, disrupted river connectivity caused by embankments, roads, railways and settlements, agricultural encroachment, habitat destruction, bird hunting, and delayed restoration planning. These pressures are shrinking wetland area, endangering migratory birds, reducing biodiversity, and undermining local food and livelihood security in Bihar. <br><br> <b>Sources:</b><ul><li><a href='https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/bihars-delay-in-clearing-restoration-plan-for-kanwar-lake-bad-news-for-bird-population-say-experts' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.downtoearth.org.in/environment/bihars-delay-in-clearing-restoration-plan-for-kanwar-lake-bad-news-for-bird-population-say-experts</a></li><li><a href='https://www.downtoearth.org.in/food/world-wetlands-day-2026-flood-prone-bihars-sponges-are-drying-up' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff;'>https://www.downtoearth.org.in/food/world-wetlands-day-2026-flood-prone-bihars-sponges-are-drying-up</a></li></ul>","images/kanwar.png"
72,"Lake","Muchalinda","Bihar",24.694444,84.991389,"Historically, Muchalinda Lake in Bodh Gaya is linked to an early Buddhist tradition stating that, during Siddhartha’s meditation, a violent storm arose and the serpent king Muchalinda sheltered him beneath his hood. This legend embedded the lake within Bodh Gaya’s long pilgrimage history and enduring sacred geography for centuries there. <br><br> <a href='https://visitplacesindia.com/attraction/muchalinda-lake-lotus-pond-bodhgaya' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Muchalinda Lake in Bodh Gaya functions as a sacred Buddhist site centered on the legend of the serpent king Muchalinda protecting the meditating Buddha. The central statue, inscribed rocks, and tranquil setting sustain practices of meditation, reflection, and pilgrimage, symbolizing resilience, spiritual protection, enlightenment, and inner peace for devotees today. <br><br> <a href='https://biharyatra.in/html/muchalinda.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Muchalinda episode emerges from one of Buddhism’s earliest serpent legends, preserved in the Vinaya Pitaka, Nidanakatha, Lalitavistara, and Mahavastu. The paper shows how this scriptural narrative shaped iconographic memory, transforming Buddha’s post-enlightenment sheltering into a portable sacred motif circulating from Bodhgaya to southeast Bengal and across Buddhist Asia. <br><br> <a href='https://www.academia.edu/109290276/From_Bodhgaya_to_South_East_Bengal_The_Images_of_Muchalinda_Buddha' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","images/muchalinda.png"
73,"Lake","Barua Sagar","Uttar Pradesh",25.379936,78.739014,"Barua Sagar Tal has historical significance as an artificial lake created around 260 years ago by Raja Udit Singh of Orchha, who constructed its embankment. Some media reports further claim that the associated dam dates to about 1694 CE, linking the site to an earlier phase of regional water engineering. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barua_Sagar_Tal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Barua Sagar Tal holds cultural and spiritual significance through its association with nearby temple remains and active shrines, including the Sheetla Mata and Shringirishi temples. The site also supports local devotional culture, especially during the annual Navratri Mela. <br><br> <a href='https://grokipedia.com/page/barua_sagar_tal' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Chandella sacred architecture as a literary-visual archive of devotion. The Ghugua Math and the richly carved Jarah-ki-Math preserve mythic imagination through iconography and sculptural narration, turning built space into cultural text within regional memory and faith. <br><br> <a href='https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.34670/mode/2up' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Barua Sagar Lake faces environmental threats from sewage discharge, detergents, and agricultural runoff. Scientific studies indicate rising nitrate concentrations, turbidity, BOD, and COD, causing oxygen stress and eutrophication risk in the ecosystem. <br><br> <a href='https://www.iosrjournals.org/iosr-jestft/papers/Vol13-%20Issue%207/Series-1/G1307015159.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/barua.png"
74,"Lake","Chittaura","Uttar Pradesh",27.32574,81.38628,"Historically, Chittaura Jheel is associated with the 1033 battle in which Raja Suhaldev is said to have defeated Ghazi Saiyyad Salar Masud. Its later memorial history includes a 1950 commemorative fair, the 1954 formation of the Shri Suhaldev Smarak Samiti, and the construction of a Suhaldev temple at the site. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chittaura_Jheel' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Chittaura Jheel holds cultural and spiritual significance as a Hindu pilgrimage landscape associated with the sage Ashtavakra, locally remembered as Ashtwarka Muni, whose ritual bathing here is believed to have restored his body. The site also includes Raja Suhaldev Darbar and a Durga temple, where seasonal fairs sustain devotional memory today. <br><br> <a href='https://grokipedia.com/page/chittaura_jheel' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","Illegal exploitation of economically important fish species, particularly Heteropneustes fossilis and Mystus, as a major environmental threat to Chittaura Jheel. It further indicates ecological vulnerability by emphasizing the urgent need for conservation measures and scientific management to preserve the wetland’s biodiversity, ecological balance, and long-term sustainability there. <br><br> <a href='https://ijarbs.com/pdfcopy/2021/feb2021/ijarbs1.pdf' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/chittaura.png"
75,"Lake","Gokul Barrage","Uttar Pradesh",27.443129,77.716168,"Historically, the Gokul Barrage, also known as the Mathura Barrage, was planned as a major water-management project near Mathura and was proposed for completion by March 2003. Opened in 2003, it was intended to supply 30 cusecs of water to Mathura and Vrindavan and 115 cusecs to Agra city region. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gokul_barrage' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Gokul is represented as a sacred cultural landscape deeply associated with Lord Krishna’s childhood, where temples, streets, and ghats embody living devotional memory. The site’s spiritual significance lies in its atmosphere of calm worship, narrative sacredness, and enduring Vaishnava tradition, making it an important locus of pilgrimage and religious heritage. <br><br> <a href='https://www.soil2soulexpeditions.com/spiritual-journey/visit-gokul-temples' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","At Gokul Barrage, the Yamuna faces severe environmental stress from untreated domestic and industrial wastewater, toxic froth, algal growth, and direct waste discharge. Low river flow and sudden water releases worsen pollution by disturbing organic deposits, depleting oxygen, and further damaging water quality, local aquatic life, and riverine biodiversity overall. <br><br> <a href='https://grokipedia.com/page/gokul_barrage' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/gokul.png"
76,"Lake","Matsyagandha","Bihar",25.904167,86.5875,"Matsyagandha Lake was conceptualized in 1996 by Saharsa Collector Tej Narayan Lal Das, transforming wasteland previously used for cremation. Owing to prolonged neglect, the lake steadily shrank between 2006 and 2017 and nearly vanished by 2018. In 2020, Bihar authorities initiated a major restoration and redevelopment plan for tourism purposes. <br><br> <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matsyagandha_Lake' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","Historically, Matsyagandha Lake functioned as an important cultural and ritual site in Saharsa, especially during Chhath Puja, which was celebrated there with great communal enthusiasm. Even when the lake dried, residents excavated patches to access water, underscoring the site’s continuing spiritual significance and collective devotional attachment for local communities alike. <br><br> <a href='https://www.livehindustan.com/bihar/saharsa/story-saharsa-matsyagandha-lake-2295745.html' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","To be updated","Matsyagandha Lake faces serious environmental threats from sedimentation, solid waste accumulation, and broader human pressures. The study identifies elevated microbial contamination, high turbidity, and increased ammonia as signs of pollution stress, largely driven by open defecation, agricultural runoff, and inadequate catchment management, all of which endanger the lake’s ecological balance. <br><br> <a href='https://www.researchgate.net/publication/398445103_Water_Quality_Assessment_of_Matsyagandha_Lake_in_Saharsa_Bihar' target='_blank' style='color: #007bff; font-weight: bold;'>Read More</a>","images/matsyagandha.png"
